>
	<p>
		This is my <strong>daemon</strong> — a living snapshot of how I operate: what I'm working on,
		why it matters, and what I'm looking for. It's written for two kinds of readers: people, and
		the AI agents that increasingly read on their behalf. If you're either, this is the fastest
		way to understand whether we should be working together.
	</p>

	<h2>Mission</h2>
	<p>
		Help societies navigate the transition from AI consumer to trusted AI contributor — starting
		where the stakes are highest: the critical infrastructure and essential systems that
		civilization depends on.
	</p>

	<h2>The problems I'm working on</h2>
	<ul>
		<li>
			<strong>Critical infrastructure is dangerously exposed to AI.</strong> The plants, utilities,
			and regulated manufacturing society quietly runs on are being handed AI tools nobody has
			taught them to trust — or to question.
		</li>
		<li>
			<strong>Institutions decide disconnected from evidence.</strong> Critical decisions get made
			on optics and politics while real risk compounds. Systems thinking loses to short-term theatre.
		</li>
		<li>
			<strong>Society is losing its capacity for rational discourse.</strong> The problems that need
			collective intelligence are getting harder while our shared ability to reason about them shrinks.
		</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>What I actually do</h2>
	<p>
		I translate — between AI capability, OT reality, and the people accountable for these systems.
		My work sits where operational technology meets AI: plant floors, utilities, and EU-regulated
		manufacturing, where a security decision is also a safety, compliance, and production decision
		at once. IEC 62443. NIS2. The EU AI Act. And a system that can't simply be switched off because
		a vendor shipped a patch.
	</p>

	<h2>Background</h2>
	<p>
		Thirty years across the domains that protecting critical infrastructure actually demands —
		military operations, physical security, ICS/OT cybersecurity, and now AI. Most careers go deep
		in one. I've spent mine learning to translate between them.
	</p>
	<p><em>Credentials: CPP · GICSP · GRID · IEC 62443 · GIAC Advisory Board.</em></p>

	<h2>Projects</h2>
	<ul>
		<li>
			<strong>This blog</strong> — thinking in public about AI in OT: what AI can actually do, what
			an OT environment will tolerate, and what the people accountable for these systems need to decide.
		</li>
		<li>
			<strong>A local, offline RAG for sensitive industrial documentation</strong> — a private LLM
			that never sends a document to the cloud, built for regulated environments. Code is public:
			<a href="https://github.com/dantsu-ai/rag1" target="_blank" rel="noopener">dantsu-ai/rag1</a>.
		</li>
		<li>
			<strong>Ongoing writing</strong> at the intersection of OT security, AI, and EU regulation.
		</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>How I think</h2>
	<ul>
		<li>
			<strong>Systems thinking first.</strong> Most problems worth caring about are systems problems
			being treated as isolated incidents.
		</li>
		<li>
			<strong>The Star Trek compass.</strong> The healthiest version of civilization runs on curiosity
			and knowledge — not wealth, power, or tribe. Evidence and rational discourse matter.
		</li>
		<li>
			<strong>Age is deployment, not decline.</strong> Cross-domain pattern recognition is the whole point.
		</li>
		<li>
			Shaped by <em>Sapiens</em>, <em>Man's Search for Meaning</em>, <em>Deep Work</em>,
			<em>Konec prokrastinace</em> — and a lifelong Star Trek habit.
		</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>What I'm offering</h2>
	<p>
		Honest translation between the technical and institutional worlds of OT and AI — capability,
		constraint, and consequence held in the same frame. If you're accountable for these systems and
		need someone who can speak to the engineers and to the board in the same conversation, that's the work.
	</p>

	<h2>What I'm looking for</h2>
	<p>
		A small number of people doing serious work at the same intersection — OT, AI, and institutional
		decision-making. I'm not here to build an audience; I'm writing toward peers. If that's you,
		get in touch.
	</p>

